ADMIN DASHBOARD – TEST CASES & VALIDATIONS

1. COMPONENT: Theme Toggle Switch (Dark Mode)
Requirement: Must be present in the header next to the title.
Switches between Light Mode and Dark Mode by changing CSS variables via :has(#darktheme:checked).
Accepts only boolean checked states.
No .dark-mode class is used — instead, theme colors update through CSS custom properties.

VALID INPUTS: Checkbox checked → Applies Dark Mode colors (--bg-color, --text-color, etc.) from dark theme variables.
              Checkbox unchecked → Restores Light Mode colors from default variables.

INVALID INPUTS: Checkbox not present in DOM → UI will not allow theme switching.
                Incorrect CSS selector for dark theme state → Theme won’t update when toggled.

2. COMPONENT: Sidebar Navigation Links (Home, Users, Settings)
Requirement: Required in the .sidebar section.
             Must be underlined and evenly aligned vertically.
             Must be purple (--link-color: #4b0082) in Light Mode and change to lavender (#9f7aea) in Dark Mode.

VALID INPUTS: <a href="#">Home</a> → Visible, underlined, clickable.
              <a href="#">Users</a> → Visible, underlined, clickable.
              <a href="#">Settings</a> → Visible, underlined, clickable.
              Link color changes appropriately in Dark Mode.

INVALID INPUTS: Links missing → Breaks navigation usability.
                Wrong variable usage → Colors remain same across both themes.

3. COMPONENT: Layout Structure (Grid Areas)
Requirement:Must use CSS Grid with grid-template-areas for layout.

Expected Alignment:
Header: Top row, full width.
Sidebar: Left column, fixed width (200px).
Main: Right column, takes remaining space.
Footer: Bottom row, full width.
Must remain responsive on resize.

VALID INPUTS: All sections (header, .sidebar, main, footer) in correct grid areas.
              Sidebar width fixed at 200px.
              Layout adapts without breaking on window resize.

INVALID INPUTS:Missing or incorrect grid-area names.
Removing display: grid; from .theme-wrapper → Layout stacks vertically.

CSS STYLING BREAKDOWN – STRUCTURED OVERVIEW
1. ELEMENT: body
            Controls global background and text color via CSS variables.
            Light Mode → White background, black text.
            Dark Mode → Dark background, white text.

2. ELEMENT: .theme-wrapper
            CSS Grid container for layout.
            grid-template-columns: 200px 1fr → Sidebar fixed, main flexible.
            Defines header, sidebar, main, and footer placement.

3. ELEMENT: header
            Green background (--header-bg).
            Flex layout → Title left, toggle switch right.
            Text always white for contrast.

4. ELEMENT: .sidebar
            Light gray background in Light Mode, dark gray in Dark Mode.
            Navigation links underlined, purple in Light Mode, lavender in Dark Mode.
            Extra width for better spacing.

5. ELEMENT: main
            White background in Light Mode, dark in Dark Mode.
            Padding for content spacing.
            Inherits text color from theme.

6. ELEMENT: footer
            Green background, white centered text.

7. ELEMENT: #darktheme (Checkbox)
            Scaled for better visibility.
            Accent color matches link color.

LEARNING OUTCOMES:
1. Built a responsive admin dashboard layout using semantic HTML + CSS Grid.
2. Implemented Light/Dark theme toggle using CSS variables & :has() selector.
3. Practiced theme-based dynamic styling without adding extra classes.
4. Structured navigation for both usability and accessibility.
5. Understood how fixed & flexible columns work in CSS Grid layouts.

